ess the consequences of industrialization and urbanization. By extending the reach of schools, broadening their mandate, and expanding their authority over the well-being of children, the state assumed a defining role in the education—and in the lives—of American families. In School, Society, and State, Steffes returns the state to the study of the history of education and brings the schools back into our discussion of state power during a pivotal moment in American political development.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aDemocracy and educationzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aEducation and statezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aEducation, CompulsoryzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aEducational changezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aEducational sociologyzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aSchool management and organizationzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aSchoolsxCentralizationzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  agovernment, education, democracy, public school, reform, progressive era, urbanization, industrialization, authority, children, management, administration, history, politics, centralization, power, state control, capitalism, localism, collectivism, individualism, sociology, law, political science, state-building, personal responsibility, success, failure, academic achievement, learning outcomes, nonfiction.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022677209740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226772127423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226772127/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles